author: @FullmetalAngyl
text: There was a beloved mod in 1.7.10.  The Villager's Nose.  Someone remade it for 1.14.4.  With a pair of shears you could snip off a villager's nose.  The nose would be dropped as an item and the villager would looked surprised and scurry into the nearest house, like you flipped his skirt.  But the noses could be planted in farm land to grow a new villager like crops.  Imagine just running around with a bunch of villager noses in your pocket.  You'd be able to create villagers anywhere without having to transport them.

author: @FullmetalAngyl
text: Back before 1.8.0 I had a superflat where I was curing zombie villagers.  Made a village out of birch logs for pillars and dark oak planks and topped the birch pillars with leaves so it looked like living structures.  Made me hungry because the village looked like dark chocolate ice cream with whipped cream and chocolate sprinkles.  Probably the only person on that server with villagers at the time.  I knew about the farming mechanic coming out in 1.8.0 so I built it around a farm and rigged it with the old redstone tracks and minecart to run under it for autofarming.  Loved that skyblock.  Made a cobble super flat and was making little biomes and had a rail system that followed the edge.  Had a lot of fun making cool stuff like the village.  For curing villagers I had set up a chute like they have for cattle.  The zombies were lured into chambers with roofs.  Really miss that game, but it was around a decade ago.

author: @asaf-oros007
text:
I've got myself a superflat world in which I decided to challenge myself to play without structures. So I've started only with the bonus chest, which gave me a few pieces of wood and 2 apples (for the villagers). I have managed to build myself a path finding mob farm and after a lot of hours I got my iron. I managed to save 2 villagers and got wood from the wandering trader.
I wanted to get lava on my world, without cheating of course, but there isnt a way yet even in 1.21. I knew about that I could downgrade my world to version beta 1.9 prerelease (to get a nether portal) in which superflat didn't exist. I tried to search for tutorials on the internet on how to do it, but didn't find any. Anyways after a lot of struggle and hours I managed to do it on my own. It worked, I had a nether portal in my world. In my world I am currently 572 minecraft days in but I still feel like it's cheating in a way, y'know? Would you consider this as cheating? I've been thinking for a few days now.

author: @Phazer25
text: gold is possible in your skyblock without the nether - use endermen to pick up grass and move it to a different biome (plains or taiga work), get pigs spawning. bonemeal carrots to breed them. then drown some zombies to get copper for a lightning rod. strike the pigs with lightning for zpiglins, and kill em for gold. this is how we did it in the carpet sky additions mod.

A more lategame method of getting lava would have been villagers giving lava buckets as a reward for a raid and simply making the portal frame spawn.

author: @847x
text: Hi! The reason why the skeletons didnt spawn when you had the blocks on the ground and  not a staircase is because you were standing too close. Mobs spawn around the player in a circle, the outer limit of the circle is 128 blocks, but there is also an inner limit, which is 16 blocks and it prevents from creepers and such spawning 2 blocks in front of you and blowing up in your face. The staircase worked because it made you more than 16 blocks away from the lower blocks on the  (also because as you said there is now fewer spawning room below the nether roof) but you still wasted the spawning potential of the 16 blocks below you. the ideal way to go about it would be to place them flat, stand more than 16 blocks away and lower your simulation distance to combat the mobs under the roof. ( i think, i couldnt see it clearly in the video and some of the stuff i said might be wrong, its been a while since i played minecraft)

text: For the skeleton spawn the strat is to go and find some mushrooms and then place them around the block. author: @aaron2402
text: For anyone looking to try this the reason skeletons weren't spawning is because of a mechanic some nether mobs have where they can't spawn in a radius of mobs of the same type meaning most of the time just 10 skeletons can clog up a soulsand valley if you want to avoid grinding endermen find a soulsand valley that's either small or otherwise has few spawning spaces. Then toggle peaceful every ~15 seconds. If you use f3+P or open to LAN to stop it from pausing you can just click difficulty 4 times watch for skeletons for 15 seconds rinse repeat. (Ps gnebon has a great video on the spawning mechanic)

author: @bennettlewis5495
text:
To get the skeleton to spawn faster on the nylium, instead of just waiting, you needed to walk back and forth between two spots 128 blocks away on opposite sides of the nylium, in order to despawn the mobs that spawn constantly opening up the mob cap for new spawns.

Of course the staircase method worked well too, especially when you got significantly above y-level 32, allowing you to despawn mobs around the lava lake level, forcing new random spawns. Your tower had to be taller than 24 blocks, or else nothing would spawn while you were on it.

text:
7:45
Hey, uh, how did you fully refresh your health and hunger without losing any of your XP or consuming any of the items on your hotbar? At the top of the staircase, no less, which would have required a ton of hunger-expending jumps to reach (and which is quite a ways away from your spawn location)?

It's also very curious that you decided to voluntarily destroy all of your placed Nihilium blocks, forcing you to wait until an Enderman brought Nihilium to the roof again in order to get more wood. If you had to actually wait for an Enderman to naturally do that, I highly doubt that you would do that so carelessly and for seemingly no reason.

I apologize for the suspicion, but given the widespread faking of Minecraft content nowadays, I'm kind of obliged to ask.

author: @FewVidsJustComments
text: The most unrealistic part of all of this is his ability to respawn up there when he dies. Everyone knows you respawn in the overworld when you die, and even if you could respawn in the nether (without use of a respawn anchor I mean), the game would likely prevent you from spawning on the nether roof. So the two most likely possiblities are he either fakes the nether respawn by cutting out the part where he respawns in the overworld and teleports back to where he was, or he set a custom biome world with the nether-type world and all nether biomes

author: @hisamiyomotsu1337
text:
for reference, mobs cant spawn within 24 blocks of the player, so you cant stand in front of the nylium like that

also, the spawn speeds will worsen as mobs spawn under the roof and fill the mob cap of 70 mobs, which means nothing can spawn on the roof

also, the higher the block is the lower the spawn rates are, as the game picks a random y point within that column for a spawn attempt, so the more layers in that column the better, and so is the lower the better (which is why some farms need breaking the nether roof)

p.s. you can pearl down through the nether roof if you find a block that has no other blocks under it and pearl into the corner

author: @asaf-oros007
text:
I've got myself a superflat world in which I decided to challenge myself to play without structures. So I've started only with the bonus chest, which gave me a few pieces of wood and 2 apples (for the villagers). I have managed to build myself a path finding mob farm and after a lot of hours I got my iron. I managed to save 2 villagers and got wood from the wandering trader.
I wanted to get lava on my world, without cheating of course, but there isnt a way yet even in 1.21. I knew about that I could downgrade my world to version beta 1.9 prerelease (to get a nether portal) in which superflat didn't exist. I tried to search for tutorials on the internet on how to do it, but didn't find any. Anyways after a lot of struggle and hours I managed to do it on my own. It worked, I had a nether portal in my world. In my world I am currently 572 minecraft days in but I still feel like it's cheating in a way, y'know? Would you consider this as cheating? I've been thinking for a few day now.

author: @Innertorium
text: Assuming you got the bottles by killing witches? You can’t get them any other way as you have no sand. As for the cauldron, you don’t need bottles. You can wait for it to fill up and then collect the water directly into your bucket or just leave it in the cauldron until you need it next. As for the drip stone, yes it grows however you only need two pieces to make the full sized drip stone. You wasted an emerald for it but could always use it on a second cauldron so it’s not entirely wasted. Enjoying this though 😁

author: @AdminAlternate
text:
Here's a way to get lava that doesn't work:
1. Get a villager by using a zombie villager and a witch for weakness. (The golden apple can be obtained from smelting down gold armor from mob drops and turning that into ingots)
2. Make the villager an armorer, level him up, then hope for the 40% chance of a lava bucket.
The reason this doesn't work is because to make the villager an armorer, you need a blast furnace which isn't obtainable without stone.
Let me know if you find any other flaws in my plan.

author: @sintanan469
text:
Nothing skyblock would work just fine for all mechanics if it just spawns the end portal ring and its nine lava sources.

Mechanically the game is going to spawn Jean with her obsidian pillars, but otherwise the End would be empty.

With this caveat of end portals and the dragon fight, as far as I'm aware the only things you couldn't get would be:
Snout pattern and pigstep, since that requires bastion chests,
Dragon heads and elytra since they requires end ships,
Echo shards, swift sneak, and disc fragments since they require ancient city chests,
Enchanted golden apples (and the thing pattern) because they require loot chests,
Trail ruins music disc and pottery sherds since that takes suspicious sand and gravel,
Sponges since no elder guardians.

You can't get ore, but you can get ingots in various forms. This means you lose access to netherite and armor trimming. Deepslate, calcite, and tuff are unavailable as building blocks since they are mining only...
No amethyst clusters means no amethyst...
And then I think the spore blossom is the only lush caves addition not sold by wandering traders...

author: @channel-s3m
text:
Short summary for people who don't want to watch 10 minutes.

Idea:
He tries to get to a wandering villager to get an oak tree.

Why does he need the oak tree?:
In order to get water, which is very necessary for a villager to complete this challenge, he needs a crafting table, which he can only get through wood.

Conclusion:
This is a difficult challenge that is not easy to overcome and requires a lot of patience. That's why he's making several episodes about it because it would be too much for one episode.

author: @elbarnes
text: Great video. I thought about what all would be possible without starting in a snow biome. Witches and glowstone could be used to get blocks. From that, you could theoretically bridge out to a snowy biome if it wasn’t started there already. So you’d be able to get to the same starting point eventually. It would probably take a few years to do that though! But it’s interesting that it’s still theoretically possible to do it without starting in a snowy biome. Just a million times more annoying

author: @Illumiinarian
text: Yeah after you get the sapling it’s proved that you can get the rest. There was this one guy (martincitopants) who played sky block but he only started with the platform and the tree, no water or lava. He got iron from zombies to make a cauldron that collects water when it rains and after he got enough for one bucket, he could get the rest with glass bottles from the sand island or if you don’t have the sand island you could probably trade with the wandering trader for red sand to get the bottles. Anyway after he got the water he got emeralds in a similar way to you, through foxes, he then made a wandering trader farm to get stalactites and I don’t actually remember how he got the lava but he did get it and after that it was just sky block.
